
# Environment

## Definition

An **Environment** is an isolated workspace in Microsoft Power Platform that contains all the resources required to build business applications.

Each environment can contain:

- Dataverse
- Canvas Apps
- Model-driven Apps
- Power Automate Flows
- Business Process Flows
- Connections
- Security Configuration

## Why do we need Environments?

The main purpose of environments is to isolate resources and separate different stages of the application lifecycle.

Common examples include:

- Development
- Testing
- Production

This separation prevents developers from directly modifying production applications.

## Resource Sharing

Applications within the same environment can share the same Dataverse and resources, provided users have the appropriate security permissions.

Applications in different environments are isolated. Communication between them can be achieved using integration technologies such as APIs, Connectors, HTTP requests, or Power Automate.

## Key Points

- Environment is an isolated workspace.
- It contains all Power Platform resources.
- Resources inside the same environment can work together.
- Different environments are isolated by design.
- Environments help organize Development, Testing, and Production workloads.
